Introduction¶

As one admission test, the Scholastic Aptitude Test (SAT) is widely used by universities and colleges in the US, it is one of the most important indicators that reflect a student's academic ability. Since SAT is such a critical subject for high school students, a school with a higher average SAT score is more preferred by people than the other schools. According to the data from NECS(National Center for Educational Statistics), Asians and White both have an average SAT math score of more than 557, but Black and Hispanic all have an average SAT score of lower than 490. The data implies that the average SAT score is associated with a student's race. Thus, it would be interesting to find out whether a school's average SAT math score associates with the school's race composition. Thus, in this report, I am going to study the association between a high school's average SAT math score and the race composition of students of the school.

I am going to load a dataset that records average SAT scores for NYC public schools, and plot the histograms of average SAT math scores and four other variables that records the school's race composition. Scatter plots would be shown to naively demonstrate the association between my Y and Xs as well as other visulizations such as histograms and maps. The dataset would be introduced more in details in the Data section, a summary statistics of the dataset would be shown in the Summary Statistics section. The primary plots would be presented and explained in the Preliminary Results section, and some more advanced plots would be shown in the The Message section. Maps can be found in the Map section.

Project 1¶

Data¶

The data used in this report is obtained from NYC Open Data, it records the average SAT score in every accredited high school in New York City and other relevant information about the school. There are 435 observations in the raw data which the level of observation is school, and the data has a total of 22 variables include the ID.

The above table is called table 2, which shows the summary statistics of the dataset. The row "count" counts the number of observations for each variable, it shows that there are 374 observations. The reason the observation has fewer observations than the raw dataset is that I remove all the NAs in the raw dataset. Compared to the Black students' distribution, the distribution for Hispanics is more extreme.

Project 2¶

The Message¶

High school's average SAT math score differs accroding to its race composition. For example, schools which have around 70% of Asian students and White students on average have a higher average than schools which have only about 20% of Asians and Whites. In other word, schools which have majority of students as Blacks and Hispanic on average have a lower average than school which have very small proportion of Blacks and Hispanics.

This is the draft I make for the message visualization, it divides the high schools into 4 categories based on the proportion of Asian students and White Students, then it shows these schools' average SAT math scores in each category. But the draft has several visualization problems. For example, each histogram has different scales on its y-axis and x-axis, this problem would make the plots hard to compare. It is impossible to see which category has the highest mean score without looking at the scale carefully. Moreover, it would be better to turn off right and top axis lines since they serve no purpose here.

This is the fine-tuned version of the draft, it shows the distribution of high school's average SAT math score and the schools are divided into groups based on their proportion of Asian students and White students. From the figure, we could see a clear right shift of distribution as the proportion of Asians and Whites increases. For schools that have less than 5% of Asians and Whites, the mean of their distribution is 392, and most schools have an average SAT math score of less than 500. When it comes to 25% to 50%, the average scores of the majority of schools are still below 500, but it is obvious that much more schools have exceeded 500 or very close to 500. In addition to that, schools that have more than 50% of Asians and Whites, have a mean score of 551. The average scores of some schools even exceed 700. The result strongly suggests that high schools have higher average scores in SAT math if they have a higher proportion of Asian students and White students, which supports the result from figure 5.

Figure 9 shows the average proportion of black students in each zip-code region. Compared to figure 8, it is clear that the red region in the middle of figure 9 corresponds to the dark blue region in the middle of figure 8, which indicates that there are lots of black students in regions where have very low SAT math average. And all non-blue regions in figure 8 corresponds to the dark blue region in figure 9, which means the high SAT math average regions have very few Black students. The evidence from the map supports my previous finding that the proportion of Black students negatively associated with the high school's average SAT math score.

This map also shows the average SAT math score by zip code in New York City, but it adds a feature that could provide each region's average SAT math score, school race composition and zip code specifically. According to the map, all non-blue regions have at least 20% of Asian students and most of them have at least 10% of White students. The reddest region has on average 73% of students as Asian and 93% of students as Asian or White, the second reddest region has on average 61% of students as White and a total of 81% of students as Asian or White. However, none of the darkest blue regions has on average more than 1% of students as Asian or White. And most of the second darkest blue region follows the same pattern as the darkest blue regions. Moreover, the proportion of Asian students and White students is larger than the proportion of Blacks and Hispanics in the majority of regions that have an average SAT math score of above 500. The map suggests strong evidence of how the race composition of a high school related to the school's average SAT math score, that the proportion of Asian students and White students of a high school positively correlate with the high school's average SAT math score, and it is the opposite for the proportion of Black students and Hispanic students.

Future Step¶

So far, this analysis only uses the result from different visualizations (scatter plot, histogram, map) to study the association between a high school's race composition and the school's average SAT math score. The next step would be using linear regression which predicts a school's average SAT math score using the school's race composition. Moreover, we might need another dataset that allows us to add some control variables into the regression (income, crime rate, etc...). And some literature related to this topic needs to be reviewed to decide the final choice of control variables. The method of regression would provide us with some statistical evidence that helps this study.

Conclusion¶

In this analysis, I study the association between high school's race composition and the school's average SAT math score by using different types of visualization includes histograms, scatter plots and maps. The study uses the data from NYC Open Data which contains relevant information of every accredited high school in New York City. The results of all visualizations are consistent with the idea that the proportion of Asian students and White students positively correlated with the school's average SAT math score, and the proportion of Black students and Hispanic students negatively correlated with the school's average score. But the finding in this analysis has not been supported by strong statistical evidence, method such as regression should be used for further investigation.
